The Lagos Chamber of Commerce and Industry (LCCI), is set to hold a symposium to develop the agriculture sector in Nigeria this weekend According to LCCI, the theme of the symposium is: ‘Making Agribusiness Bankable: Lenders and Investors Expectations.’ the body said that the symposium which would take place in Lagos will feature a panel discussion and audience participation to allow for a balanced interaction, assessment, evaluation and intervention. Muda Yusuf, Director-General of LCCI in a chat with our correspondent, said the focus of the symposium was to consider agriculture finance across the entire value chain and examine different scenarios to make the agribusiness competitive. He emphasised that participants added would also deliberate on practical solutions to increase access of farmers and operators in the sector to finance, investments and intervention funds. “Stakeholders will also articulate the internal resources required for profiling projects to make agribusiness bankable and propose robust institutional supports to unleash the potentials of the sector,” he added. Yusuf also hinted that the keynote address would be delivered by Mr. Aliyu Abdulhameed, Managing Director of the Nigeria Incentive-Based Risk Sharing System for Agricultural Lending (NIRSAL Plc.). He stated that financial institutions, farmers, operators and critical stakeholders in the Nigeria economy would also attend the event.